50|$|Gomalia is a {{monotypic}} genus of hesperiid butterfly.Gomalia elma, the marbled skipper, green-marbled sandman or African <b>mallow</b> <b>skipper,</b> {{is found}} in Africa and parts of Asia.|$|E
5000|$|<b>Mallow</b> <b>skippers</b> {{lay their}} eggs {{on top of the}} leaves of {{different}} species of mallow (hence the common name of the species). The larvae mainly feed on Malva sylvestris, Malva moschata, Althaea officinalis, Lavatera thuringiaca and Hibiscus species. [...] The butterfly flies from April to October depending on the location. They get nectar from various herbaceous plants. In Central Europe usually this species has two generations (April-May and July), while in southern areas three or more generations are present. The fully grown caterpillars hibernate and pupate in the next Spring.|$|R
50|$|Carcharodus tripolinus, {{the false}} <b>mallow</b> <b>skipper,</b> is a {{butterfly}} {{of the family}} Hesperiidae. It is found along a narrow strip {{along the coast of}} southern Portugal and Spain and across North Africa.|$|E
50|$|Carcharodus alceae, the <b>mallow</b> <b>skipper,</b> is a {{butterfly}} {{of the family}} Hesperiidae. The scientific Latin species name alceae refers to the host plants Althaea, which, in turn, are named after the ancient Greek poet Alcaeus of Mytilene.|$|E

